article.description:
Brandy Reed played like she was trying to get out
of the doghouse.
article.headline: Reed scores 20 as Phoenix topples Charlotte
article.linkText: Reed tries to redeem herself with big game for Mercury
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Brandy Reed played like she was trying to get out
of the doghouse.

	   Reed's 20 points, including two free throws with 13.7 seconds
left, helped the Phoenix Mercury beat the Charlotte Sting 80-77
Sunday night for their third consecutive victory.

	   ''I wasn't as comfortable as I can be, but it felt better than
previous games,'' said Reed, who was fined an undisclosed sum Wednesday for her behavior in the June 3 game against Washington. ''It was certainly the best game of the season for me. By
practicing and spending more time with the team, I can get my
rhythm back.''

	   Reed was ineffective in the first four minutes of each half
against the Mystics, sulked on the bench and did not join the team
during timeouts. She did not score against Washington and had just
four points in the previous game.

	   Sunday, she made seven of 11 field goals and six of seven free throws,
although her turnover with 26.7 seconds left in the game helped
Charlotte nearly erase a 21-point Mercury lead.

	   Phoenix (3-1) led 57-36 after a 10-footer by Reed with 14:41
left.

	   But after Reed lost the handle on the ball trying to get it up
court, Charlotte cut it to 78-77 when Andrea Stinson made a
3-pointer with 16.2 seconds left.

	   Reed made the final two points after being fouled by Allison
Feaster on the ensuing inbounds play.

	   ''This was the Brandy we've been waiting to see,'' said Phoenix
coach Cynthia Cooper.

	   Both Stinson and Feaster each missed 20-footers in the final 10
seconds as the Sting (2-3) lost for the third time in a row.

	   Charlotte coach Anne Donovan saw her team go on runs of 12-2 and
13-3 to close to 76-72 with 1:06 left.

	   ''We could have used a few more minutes to keep coming back, but
we just ran out of time,'' Donovan said.

	   Stinson had 24 points and eight rebounds, and Dawn Staley 19
points for the Sting.

	   Jennifer Gillom scored 14 points and Slobodanka Tuvic added 10
points and five rebounds for Phoenix, which led 46-31 at halftime.
